    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Iraq Deal: War Averted, or Just Delayed?; End to U.S. Largess</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Timothy P O'Neill letter contends that Congress must consider US missions to Persian Gulf and other countries when considering back dues to United Nations</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Secretary General Kofi Annan, returning from what he terms successful negotations with Saddam Hussein, claimed that President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain acted as ''perfect U.N. peacekeepers'' who knew that ''the best way to use force is to show it in order not to use it'' (news article, Feb. 25).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Secretary General Kofi Annan, returning from what he terms successful negotations with Saddam Hussein, claimed that President Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain acted as ''perfect U.N. peacekeepers'' who knew that ''the best way to use force is to show it in order not to use it'' (news article, Feb. 25).</p>
        <p>The question becomes who should foot the bill for this American show of force. Mr. Annan now appears ready to turn up the heat on Congress and demand payment of $1.5 billion in back dues. Congress must make it plain that our military is not a charity and that the missions to Bosnia, Haiti and the Persian Gulf will be charged against dues.</p>
        <p>TIMOTHY P. O'NEILL  Marco Island, Fla., Feb. 25, 1998</p>
      </block>
